{"title_page": "Fry family (chocolate)", "text_new": "{{about|the Fry family associated with Bristol and Quakers|other Fry families |Fry family}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n\nThis '''Fry family''' was prominent in England, especially [[Bristol]], in the [[Society of Friends]], and in the [[confectionery]] business in the 18th, 19th, and early 20th centuries under the company name [[J. S. Fry & Sons]]. They intermarried with many of the other prominent [[Quaker]] families and were involved in business and social and philanthropic causes.\n\n==Origins==\nThe earliest ancestor that can be reliably traced is John Frye, who was born about 1474 in [[Wiltshire]].<ref>John P. Fry (1906) Pedigree of the Family of Fry.</ref>  He married Johanna (possibly Bray) about 1499 in [[Corston, Wiltshire|Corston]].  Some genealogies say his parents were Richard Frye (1445\u20131504) and Joan Beaufort (1433\u20131518), great granddaughter of [[John of Gaunt]], but there is doubt about the linkage.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Fry\n  | first = Theodore\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = A brief memoir of Francis Fry, F.S.A. of Bristol\n  | publisher = \"Barclay & Fry\"\n  | year = 1887\n  | location =\n  | pages =\n  | url =https://archive.org/details/abriefmemoirfra01frygoog\n  | doi =\n    }}</ref> \n\nJohn and Johanna had a son John Frye, who was born in 1500 in Corston.<ref>{{cite web|title=5 John Fry|url=http://www.frenchaymuseumarchives.co.uk/Archives/FryBooks/Vol-1/Page-005-JohnFry.htm|website=Frenchay Museum|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>  He in turn is an ancestor of Zephaniah Fry (1658\u20131728), who was the first known member of the family to embrace the Quaker faith; he did so while still single and became a leader of his local Quaker meeting in [[Kington Langley]].<ref name=\"british-history.ac.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/wilts/vol14/pp221-229|title=Parishes: Sutton Benger {{!}} British History Online|website=www.british-history.ac.uk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>  A record of one meeting held in their house is given in [[George Fox]]\u2019s Journals: \"At ... Frye\u2019s in Wiltshire we had a very blessed meeting and quiet, though the officers had purposed to break it up by thieves, and they were required to go back again with speed, to search after and pursue them; by which our meeting escaped disturbance and we were preserved out of their hands.\"  However, meetings of more than five persons were forbidden by the [[Conventicle Act 1664|Conventicle Act]], and, once arrested, Quakers would be ordered to take the oath of allegiance, which they refused to do, taking the command \u2018Swear not at all\u2019 literally.  Zephaniah was arrested in 1683 and sent to [[Ilchester]] Gaol for three months, but \"emerged unscarred\".<ref>Spalding, Frances: Roger Fry, Art and Life</ref>  Zephaniah was a cloth worker, as seen from this quote \"There was a fuller in the parish in 1611, and clothworkers, among whom were Zephaniah Fry (d. 1724) and his son Zephaniah (d. 1716), in the later 17th century and the 18th.\"<ref name=\"british-history.ac.uk\"/>\n\nZephaniah married Jane Smith on 8 April 1686 in [[Marden, Wiltshire]].<ref>England & Wales, Quaker Birth, Marriage, and Death Registers, 1578\u20131837</ref><ref>Wiltshire, England, Marriages, 1538-1837</ref> and lived in [[Sutton Benger]], Wiltshire.  Their youngest son, John, described them as \"industrious, frugal, pious\".  Zephaniah died on 4 May 1724.  Jane died on 15 November 1731 in Sutton Benger.<ref>Wiltshire, England, Quaker Deaths, 1542-1897</ref>  Zephaniah and Jane had four sons and four daughters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zephaniah Fry|url=http://www.frenchaymuseumarchives.co.uk/Archives/FryBooks/Vol-1/Page-004-ZephaniaFry.htm|website=Frenchay Museum|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe patriarch of the most important branch of the family was Zephaniah's son, John Fry (1701\u20131775).<ref>Dates of Birth and Death of John Fry (1701\u20131775) are given in a catalogue entry in the online catalogue of the Library of the Society of Friends: ''Lately published (price 1s. 6d.) and sold by the author at Sutton Benger near Chippenham, Wilts; and by his sons Joseph Fry, apothecary in Bristol, and John Fry, cheesemonger in White-chapel, London: An alphabetical extract of all the annual printed [[Epistle (Quaker)|epistles]], which have been sent to the several quarterly-meetings of the people called Quakers, ... A proposal. As there remain, now unsold, but a few copies ... Those counties that are willing to encourage the printing a second edition, are desired to send their subscriptions to Luke Hinde, in George-yard, Lombard-street, where the subscribers will be supplied at ten-pence per book. - [London, 1765?].''</ref>  John moved to London at the age of 13 or 14, probably to take up an apprenticeship, but he disliked London.  He is identified as the John Fry of [[Melksham]] whose clocks sometimes appear at auction, though it is possible that it was his son who was the clockmaker.  He appears to have already made his fortune by the age of 25 and married Mary Storrs (b. 25 February 1702) of [[Chesterfield]], [[Derbyshire]], on 23 March 1727<ref>\nEngland & Wales, Quaker Birth, Marriage, and Death Registers, 1578-1837 for John Fry  Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire  Piece 1034: Monthly Meeting of Chesterfield (1641-1775)</ref> whom he met while in London. With his wife, John returned to Sutton Benger, where he built a small house, carved their initials above the door, fathered six children, employed one servant, and enjoyed to the end of his days a quiet, rural life.  His house was certified for Quaker meetings.  He was active in the unpaid ministry of the Society of Friends and wrote poetry; he was also an author.  He published a Quaker book of ''Selected Poems Containing Religious Epistle etc.'' which was prefaced \"Sutton Benger 25th March 1774\".<ref>John Fry (1774) Select Poems: Containing Religious Epistles, &C., Occasionally Written on Various Subjects.</ref>\n\nJohn's son, William Storrs Fry (1736\u20131808) was probably born in Wiltshire, where his parents stayed when he moved to London.  He married Elizabeth Lambert from [[Walsingham]], Norfolk on 2 June 1769. William was a tea dealer, though Elizabeth is credited as being the one with \"the financial acumen which had enabled money both to be acquired and prudently managed: it was a quality which perhaps neither of the sons inherited\".<ref name=\"Milligan\"/>  William and Elizabeth lived in [[Plashet|Plashet House]], a mansion in East Ham, which passed into the hands of William Storrs Fry in 1787.\n\nWilliam was the father of [[Joseph Fry (tea merchant)|Joseph Fry]] (1777\u20131861) the tea merchant who married the prison reformer [[Elizabeth Fry]] n\u00e9e Gurney (1780\u20131845). William Storrs Fry (1806\u20131844) was one of the 11 children of Joseph and Elizabeth Fry; he married Sally Juliana Pelly, daughter of [[Sir John Pelly, 1st Baronet|Sir John Henry Pelly]], first baronet Pelly, governor of the Bank of England.\n\n==The start of the chocolate dynasty==\n\nJohn Fry's other son, [[Joseph Fry (type-founder)|Joseph Fry]] (1728\u20131787), was apprenticed to Henry Portsmouth of [[Basingstoke]] as an [[apothecary]] and doctor. He married Portsmouth's daughter, Anna (1719/20\u20131803). Joseph Fry founded a [[chocolate]] company called Fry, Vaughan & Co. in [[Bristol]]. He also founded Fry and Pine, later Joseph Fry & Co., a [[type setting|typefoundry]].\n\n==Typefounding Frys==\n{{main article|Edmund Fry}}\nJoseph Fry & Co., the typefoundry, was continued by Joseph Fry's middle son, [[Edmund Fry]] (1757\u20131835)<ref>See DNB [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]], 2015 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/10207] accessed 25 10 2015.</ref> and renamed Edmund Fry & Co. Edmund had two sons who survived to adulthood: Windover (1797\u20131835) and Arthur (1809\u20131878). Windover joined him in the business.<ref>Windover Fry, Typefounder was listed as bankrupt 20 July 1824 in [https://archive.org/details/bankruptdirecto00elwigoog/page/n163 <!-- pg=153 quote=fry windover. --> ''The Bankrupt Directory'' By George Elwick (1843) pg.153 (on Googlebooks)]</ref>  An example of a font that the firm designed is ''Fry's Ornamented''.<ref>[http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/artypes/frys-ornamented/familytree.html Fry\u2019s Ornamented typeface]</ref>\n\n==Chocolate-making Frys==\n[[File:Joseph Fry.jpg|thumb|upright|In the 1850s, Englishman [[Joseph Storrs Fry|Joseph Fry]] invented the world's first [[Chocolate bar|solid chocolate]].<ref>{{cite|url=http://facts-about-chocolate.com/chocolate-history/|title=Chocolate History: Who Invented Chocolate?|work=Chocolate University|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref>]]\nAfter Joseph Fry's death in 1787 his wife, Anna Fry, took over the chocolate company and it was renamed Anna Fry & Son. Their son was the first [[Joseph Storrs Fry]] (1769\u20131835) who, after his mother's death, renamed the firm [[J. S. Fry & Sons]] under which name it became quite well known. Joseph Storrs Fry was the first to introduce factory methods into the making of chocolate and the first to use a [[James Watt|Watt's]] steam engine to grind the beans.\n\nThe sons of Joseph Storrs Fry and his wife Ann Allen (1764?\u20131829) are\n*Joseph Fry (1795\u20131879) (''See below'')\n*[[Francis Fry]] (1803\u20131886) (''See below'')\n*Richard Fry (d.1878)\nThey also had four daughters.  The sons all became partners in the firm.\n\n==Francis Fry (1803\u20131886)==\n{{main article|Francis Fry}}\nFrancis Fry was the son of Joseph Storrs Fry and his wife Ann Allen.<ref>[[ODNB]] article by David J. Hall, \u2018Fry, Francis (1803\u20131886)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/10209], accessed 13 Sept 2007.</ref> Besides the directorship of the chocolate firm, he was also involved in porcelain, typefounding, the [[Bristol Water]]works where he was a director, and railways (including the [[Bristol and Gloucester Railway]]). He was also a well known collector of old Bibles. He headed the firm when it started producing the first chocolate bars in 1847.\n\nHe married Matilda Penrose (circa 1808\u20131888). They had four sons and three daughters including:\n*Francis James Fry (1835 \u2013 15 November 1918) (''See below'')\n*Theodore Fry (''See below'').\n\n===Francis James Fry (1835\u20131918) and his family===\nF.J. Fry was the son of Francis Fry (1803\u20131886). He was [[High Sheriff of Bristol|Sheriff of Bristol]] in 1887. He married twice and had two daughters and four sons.<ref>F.J. Fry entry in ''Who was Who''.</ref>\n[[File:Norahcooke-hurleblueplaque.JPG|thumb|Blue Plaque for Norah Cooke-Hurle in [[Brislington]].]]\nHis daughter, [[Norah Fry|Norah Cooke-Hurle born Fry]] (1871\u20131960), was an advocate of better services for people with learning difficulties.<ref>[http://www.bris.ac.uk/depts/NorahFry/norah.htm University of Bristol Norah Fry Research Centre: Brief biography of Norah Cooke-Hurle]</ref> In 1988, the University of Bristol named their new research centre after Norah Fry, because she did so much for people with learning difficulties.\n\nOne of his sons was [[Sir Geoffrey Fry, 1st Baronet|Geoffrey Storrs Fry]] (1888\u20131960), from 1929, the first (and last) Baronet Fry of [[Oare, Wiltshire|Oare]] in Wiltshire. He was private secretary to [[Bonar Law]] and [[Stanley Baldwin]]. He married Alathea Gardner, the second daughter of Lord Burghclere.<ref>G.S. Fry's entry in ''Who was Who''.</ref><ref>''The Times'', Saturday, 15 October 1960; pg. 8; Issue 54903; col G: Obituary Sir Geoffrey Fry.</ref><ref>''The Times'', Friday, 28 May 1915; pg. 11; Issue 40866; col C: Forthcoming marriages.</ref>\n*[[Jennifer Ross|(Ann) Jennifer Evelyn Elizabeth Fry]] (1916\u20132003), only child of Geoffrey and Alathea Fry. She was the wife of [[Alan Ross]], the poet.\n\n===Theodore Fry and his family===\n[[Theodore Fry]] (1836\u20131912), was the son of Francis Fry (1803\u20131886). He was Liberal MP for [[Darlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Darlington]] and made baronet.  His wife, [[Sophia Fry]] n\u00e9e Pease (1837\u20131897) was a prominent philanthropist and political activist.<ref>''Times obituary'' of Theodore Fry is at [http://www.dmm.org.uk/archives/a_obit15.htm Durham Mining Museum website].</ref> Their son, John Pease Fry (1864\u20131957),<ref>J.P. Fry entry in ''Who was Who''.</ref> the second baronet, became Chairman and managing director of Bearpark Coal & Coke of [[Durham, England|Durham]].\n\n==Joseph Fry and his family==\n\nJoseph Fry (1795\u20131879),<ref>Note: he was not the Joseph Fry (1777\u20131861), who was husband of [[Elizabeth Fry]]</ref> son of the first Joseph Storrs Fry (1769\u20131835), and Mary Anne Swaine (1797\u20131886)<ref name=\"Milliagn\">''[[Milligan's Biographical dictionary of British Quakers in commerce and industry|The Biographical dictionary of British Quakers in commerce and industry]], 1775-1920'', by Edward H. Milligan, Sessions of York (2007) {{ISBN|978-1-85072-367-7}}. p191: article on Joseph Fry (1795-1879).</ref> were the parents of:\n*[[Joseph Storrs Fry II]] (1826\u20131913). Headed the chocolate firm after 1886 and was active in the Society of Friends. He never married but was known for his philanthropy.\n*Sir [[Edward Fry]] (1827\u20131918), a judge on the British Court of Appeal. Edward Fry was the father of the art critic and artist [[Roger Fry]] and the social reformers, [[Joan Mary Fry]] (1862\u20131955), [[Margery Fry]] (1874\u20131958) and [[Ruth Fry]] (1878\u20131962). His daughter, Agnes Fry (1869\u20131958) compiled his biography.\n*Albert Fry (1830?\u20131903). He worked with [[John Fowler (agricultural engineer)|John Fowler]] (1826\u20131864)<ref>See [[ODNB]] article by Jonathan Brown, \u2018Fowler, John (1826\u20131864)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, Sept 2004; online edn, May 2007 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/10010], accessed 15 Sept 2007.</ref> to develop and manufacture a drainage plough in the mid-19th century. He founded the [[Bristol Wagon & Carriage Works]].<ref>{{cite journal|last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date= 24 April 1903 |title=Obituary of Albert Fry |journal=\"The Times\" |volume= |issue=37063 |page=10 |url=}}</ref> He was a chairman of the council of the [[University of Bristol]] and, along with other members of his family and of the Wills family, a major donor<ref>''The Library of the University of Bristol, 1876-1975'' by Nicholas Lee at [http://www.bris.ac.uk/is/about/what/libraries/libraryhistory-lee.doc http://www.bris.ac.uk/is/about/what/libraries/libraryhistory-lee.doc] accessed 15 Sept 2007.</ref>\n*Susan Ann Fry (1829\u20131917) married in 1856, as his third wife, Thomas Pease and was the mother of [[Edward Reynolds Pease]] who help found the [[Fabian Society]]<ref name=\"Milligan\">''The Biographical dictionary of British Quakers in commerce and industry, 1775-1920'', by Edward H Milligan, Sessions of York (2007) {{ISBN|978-1-85072-367-7}}. pp.190B-191A.</ref> and Marian Fry Pease (1859\u20131954) who was the first female student and later a teacher at [[University College, Bristol]].<ref>John B. Thomas, \u2018Pease, Marian Fry (1859\u20131954)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/48581, accessed 26 May 2014]</ref>\n*[[Lewis Fry]] (1832\u20131921) was the Liberal, later Liberal Unionist, MP for Bristol from 1878 until 1886 and from 1895 until 1900. He was chairman of Parliamentary Committee on Town Holdings, 1886\u20131892.<ref>Lewis Fry entry in ''Who was Who''</ref>  He was a member of the [[Privy Council]]. He was the first chairman of the Council of the University of Bristol.\n*Henrietta Jane Fry (1840\u20131911) who married an ironfounder named William Whitwell in 1862.<ref name=\"Milligan\"/>\nand three other daughters, one of whom died in infancy.<ref name=\"Milligan\"/>\n\n==Other members of the family==\n\n*[[Cecil Roderick Fry]] (1890\u20131952)<ref>C.R. Fry entry in ''Who was Who''.</ref> was the last member of the family to head the chocolate firm before it merged with [[Cadburys]].\n**[[Jeremy Fry]] (1924\u20132005) was an engineer and inventor, son of Cecil Fry. Founded [[Rotork]].\n** David Fry (1918\u20131967), engineer, son of Cecil Fry.  Founded Frenchay Products.\n*[[Edwin Waterhouse]], co-founder of the accountancy practice of [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]].  His great-grandmother, Anne Fry (1755-1821), was the niece of the brothers [[Joseph Fry (type-founder)|Joseph Fry]] and William Storrs Fry.  Anne's father was another brother, John Fry (1733-1803).<ref>See common ancestor John Fry (1701 - 1775)[https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Fry-1728] click on \"Descendants\".</ref>{{Better source|reason=I doubt wiki tree is a good source. The line seems to be John Fry had a daughter, Ann, who married Jasper Capper and they had a daughter, Rebecca, who married Paul Bevan, and they had a daughter, Mary, who married Alfred Waterhouse and they are parents of Edwin (as well as two others with wiki articles).  However that is all original research (though one perhaps a bit more trustworthy than wikitree) from http://www.pennyghael.org.uk/Fry.pdf|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Other Frys==\n'''Other Quaker Frys who might or might not be related to this family are:'''\n\n*Catherine Fry, mother of [[Lewis Fry Richardson]], mathematician\n*[[Christopher Fry]], born Christopher Fry Harris (1907\u20132005), playwright\n\n''For other people with the surname \"Fry\" but probably ''not'' related to the Quaker Chocolate manufacturing Fry family see [[Fry (surname)]].''\n\n==Sources==\n*{{ODNBweb|id=10212|title=Fry, Joseph|last = Mosley|first=James Mosley}}; and the articles there on  Francis Fry (1803\u20131886), Edmund Fry (1754\u20131835), Joseph Storrs Fry (1826\u20131913), Edward Fry (1827\u20131918), and Sophia Fry n\u00e9e Pease.\n*[http://www.bath.ac.uk/~ensegb/wag.htm Bristol Wagon & Carriage Works] (references to Albert Fry)\n*[http://www.bris.ac.uk/university/history/ University of Bristol History] (references to the Fry family support in founding the university)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060211070915/http://www.frenchay.org/frys.html Frenchay Village Museum] \u2013 [[Frenchay]], [[South Gloucestershire]] is where many of the Frys lived\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Fry|short=x}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fry Family}}\n[[Category:Fry family| ]]\n[[Category:English families]]\n[[Category:People from Bristol]]\n[[Category:Quaker families]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Fry family associated with Bristol and Quakers|other Fry families |Fry family}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n\nThis '''Fry family''' was prominent in England, especially [[Bristol]], in the [[Society of Friends]], and in the [[confectionery]] business in the 18th, 19th, and early 20th centuries, under the company name [[J. S. Fry & Sons]]. They intermarried with many of the other prominent [[Quaker]] families and were involved in business and social and philanthropic causes.\n\n==Origins==\nThe earliest ancestor that can be reliably traced is John Frye, who was born about 1474 in [[Wiltshire]].<ref>John P. Fry (1906) Pedigree of the Family of Fry.</ref>  He married Johanna (possibly Bray) about 1499 in [[Corston, Wiltshire|Corston]].  Some genealogies say his parents were Richard Frye (1445\u20131504) and Joan Beaufort (1433\u20131518), great granddaughter of [[John of Gaunt]], but there is doubt about the linkage.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Fry\n  | first = Theodore\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = A brief memoir of Francis Fry, F.S.A. of Bristol\n  | publisher = \"Barclay & Fry\"\n  | year = 1887\n  | location =\n  | pages =\n  | url =https://archive.org/details/abriefmemoirfra01frygoog\n  | doi =\n    }}</ref> \n\nJohn and Johanna had a son John Frye, who was born in 1500 in Corston.<ref>{{cite web|title=5 John Fry|url=http://www.frenchaymuseumarchives.co.uk/Archives/FryBooks/Vol-1/Page-005-JohnFry.htm|website=Frenchay Museum|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>  He in turn is an ancestor of Zephaniah Fry (1658\u20131728), who was the first known member of the family to embrace the Quaker faith; he did so while still single and became a leader of his local Quaker meeting in [[Kington Langley]].<ref name=\"british-history.ac.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/wilts/vol14/pp221-229|title=Parishes: Sutton Benger {{!}} British History Online|website=www.british-history.ac.uk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>  A record of one meeting held in their house is given in [[George Fox]]\u2019s Journals: \"At ... Frye\u2019s in Wiltshire we had a very blessed meeting and quiet, though the officers had purposed to break it up by thieves, and they were required to go back again with speed, to search after and pursue them; by which our meeting escaped disturbance and we were preserved out of their hands.\"  However, meetings of more than five persons were forbidden by the [[Conventicle Act 1664|Conventicle Act]], and, once arrested, Quakers would be ordered to take the oath of allegiance, which they refused to do, taking the command \u2018Swear not at all\u2019 literally.  Zephaniah was arrested in 1683 and sent to [[Ilchester]] Gaol for three months, but \"emerged unscarred\".<ref>Spalding, Frances: Roger Fry, Art and Life</ref>  Zephaniah was a cloth worker, as seen from this quote \"There was a fuller in the parish in 1611, and clothworkers, among whom were Zephaniah Fry (d. 1724) and his son Zephaniah (d. 1716), in the later 17th century and the 18th.\"<ref name=\"british-history.ac.uk\"/>\n\nZephaniah married Jane Smith on 8 April 1686 in [[Marden, Wiltshire]].<ref>England & Wales, Quaker Birth, Marriage, and Death Registers, 1578\u20131837</ref><ref>Wiltshire, England, Marriages, 1538-1837</ref> and lived in [[Sutton Benger]], Wiltshire.  Their youngest son, John, described them as \"industrious, frugal, pious\".  Zephaniah died on 4 May 1724.  Jane died on 15 November 1731 in Sutton Benger.<ref>Wiltshire, England, Quaker Deaths, 1542-1897</ref>  Zephaniah and Jane had four sons and four daughters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zephaniah Fry|url=http://www.frenchaymuseumarchives.co.uk/Archives/FryBooks/Vol-1/Page-004-ZephaniaFry.htm|website=Frenchay Museum|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe patriarch of the most important branch of the family was Zephaniah's son, John Fry (1701\u20131775).<ref>Dates of Birth and Death of John Fry (1701\u20131775) are given in a catalogue entry in the online catalogue of the Library of the Society of Friends: ''Lately published (price 1s. 6d.) and sold by the author at Sutton Benger near Chippenham, Wilts; and by his sons Joseph Fry, apothecary in Bristol, and John Fry, cheesemonger in White-chapel, London: An alphabetical extract of all the annual printed [[Epistle (Quaker)|epistles]], which have been sent to the several quarterly-meetings of the people called Quakers, ... A proposal. As there remain, now unsold, but a few copies ... Those counties that are willing to encourage the printing a second edition, are desired to send their subscriptions to Luke Hinde, in George-yard, Lombard-street, where the subscribers will be supplied at ten-pence per book. - [London, 1765?].''</ref>  John moved to London at the age of 13 or 14, probably to take up an apprenticeship, but he disliked London.  He is identified as the John Fry of [[Melksham]] whose clocks sometimes appear at auction, though it is possible that it was his son who was the clockmaker.  He appears to have already made his fortune by the age of 25 and married Mary Storrs (b. 25 February 1702) of [[Chesterfield]], [[Derbyshire]], on 23 March 1727<ref>\nEngland & Wales, Quaker Birth, Marriage, and Death Registers, 1578-1837 for John Fry  Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire  Piece 1034: Monthly Meeting of Chesterfield (1641-1775)</ref> whom he met while in London. With his wife, John returned to Sutton Benger, where he built a small house, carved their initials above the door, fathered six children, employed one servant, and enjoyed to the end of his days a quiet, rural life.  His house was certified for Quaker meetings.  He was active in the unpaid ministry of the Society of Friends and wrote poetry; he was also an author.  He published a Quaker book of ''Selected Poems Containing Religious Epistle etc.'' which was prefaced \"Sutton Benger 25th March 1774\".<ref>John Fry (1774) Select Poems: Containing Religious Epistles, &C., Occasionally Written on Various Subjects.</ref>\n\nJohn's son, William Storrs Fry (1736\u20131808) was probably born in Wiltshire, where his parents stayed when he moved to London.  He married Elizabeth Lambert from [[Walsingham]], Norfolk on 2 June 1769. William was a tea dealer, though Elizabeth is credited as being the one with \"the financial acumen which had enabled money both to be acquired and prudently managed: it was a quality which perhaps neither of the sons inherited\".<ref name=\"Milligan\"/>  William and Elizabeth lived in [[Plashet|Plashet House]], a mansion in East Ham, which passed into the hands of William Storrs Fry in 1787.\n\nWilliam was the father of [[Joseph Fry (tea merchant)|Joseph Fry]] (1777\u20131861) the tea merchant who married the prison reformer [[Elizabeth Fry]] n\u00e9e Gurney (1780\u20131845). William Storrs Fry (1806\u20131844) was one of the 11 children of Joseph and Elizabeth Fry; he married Sally Juliana Pelly, daughter of [[Sir John Pelly, 1st Baronet|Sir John Henry Pelly]], first baronet Pelly, governor of the Bank of England.\n\n==The start of the chocolate dynasty==\n\nJohn Fry's other son, [[Joseph Fry (type-founder)|Joseph Fry]] (1728\u20131787), was apprenticed to Henry Portsmouth of [[Basingstoke]] as an [[apothecary]] and doctor. He married Portsmouth's daughter, Anna (1719/20\u20131803). Joseph Fry founded a [[chocolate]] company called Fry, Vaughan & Co. in [[Bristol]]. He also founded Fry and Pine, later Joseph Fry & Co., a [[type setting|typefoundry]].\n\n==Typefounding Frys==\n{{main article|Edmund Fry}}\nJoseph Fry & Co., the typefoundry, was continued by Joseph Fry's middle son, [[Edmund Fry]] (1757\u20131835)<ref>See DNB [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]], 2015 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/10207] accessed 25 10 2015.</ref> and renamed Edmund Fry & Co. Edmund had two sons who survived to adulthood: Windover (1797\u20131835) and Arthur (1809\u20131878). Windover joined him in the business.<ref>Windover Fry, Typefounder was listed as bankrupt 20 July 1824 in [https://archive.org/details/bankruptdirecto00elwigoog/page/n163 <!-- pg=153 quote=fry windover. --> ''The Bankrupt Directory'' By George Elwick (1843) pg.153 (on Googlebooks)]</ref>  An example of a font that the firm designed is ''Fry's Ornamented''.<ref>[http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/artypes/frys-ornamented/familytree.html Fry\u2019s Ornamented typeface]</ref>\n\n==Chocolate-making Frys==\n[[File:Joseph Fry.jpg|thumb|upright|In the 1850s, Englishman [[Joseph Storrs Fry|Joseph Fry]] invented the world's first [[Chocolate bar|solid chocolate]].<ref>{{cite|url=http://facts-about-chocolate.com/chocolate-history/|title=Chocolate History: Who Invented Chocolate?|work=Chocolate University|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref>]]\nAfter Joseph Fry's death in 1787 his wife, Anna Fry, took over the chocolate company and it was renamed Anna Fry & Son. Their son was the first [[Joseph Storrs Fry]] (1769\u20131835) who, after his mother's death, renamed the firm [[J. S. Fry & Sons]] under which name it became quite well known. Joseph Storrs Fry was the first to introduce factory methods into the making of chocolate and the first to use a [[James Watt|Watt's]] steam engine to grind the beans.\n\nThe sons of Joseph Storrs Fry and his wife Ann Allen (1764?\u20131829) are\n*Joseph Fry (1795\u20131879) (''See below'')\n*[[Francis Fry]] (1803\u20131886) (''See below'')\n*Richard Fry (d.1878)\nThey also had four daughters.  The sons all became partners in the firm.\n\n==Francis Fry (1803\u20131886)==\n{{main article|Francis Fry}}\nFrancis Fry was the son of Joseph Storrs Fry and his wife Ann Allen.<ref>[[ODNB]] article by David J. Hall, \u2018Fry, Francis (1803\u20131886)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/10209], accessed 13 Sept 2007.</ref> Besides the directorship of the chocolate firm, he was also involved in porcelain, typefounding, the [[Bristol Water]]works where he was a director, and railways (including the [[Bristol and Gloucester Railway]]). He was also a well known collector of old Bibles. He headed the firm when it started producing the first chocolate bars in 1847.\n\nHe married Matilda Penrose (circa 1808\u20131888). They had four sons and three daughters including:\n*Francis James Fry (1835 \u2013 15 November 1918) (''See below'')\n*Theodore Fry (''See below'').\n\n===Francis James Fry (1835\u20131918) and his family===\nF.J. Fry was the son of Francis Fry (1803\u20131886). He was [[High Sheriff of Bristol|Sheriff of Bristol]] in 1887. He married twice and had two daughters and four sons.<ref>F.J. Fry entry in ''Who was Who''.</ref>\n[[File:Norahcooke-hurleblueplaque.JPG|thumb|Blue Plaque for Norah Cooke-Hurle in [[Brislington]].]]\nHis daughter, [[Norah Fry|Norah Cooke-Hurle born Fry]] (1871\u20131960), was an advocate of better services for people with learning difficulties.<ref>[http://www.bris.ac.uk/depts/NorahFry/norah.htm University of Bristol Norah Fry Research Centre: Brief biography of Norah Cooke-Hurle]</ref> In 1988, the University of Bristol named their new research centre after Norah Fry, because she did so much for people with learning difficulties.\n\nOne of his sons was [[Sir Geoffrey Fry, 1st Baronet|Geoffrey Storrs Fry]] (1888\u20131960), from 1929, the first (and last) Baronet Fry of [[Oare, Wiltshire|Oare]] in Wiltshire. He was private secretary to [[Bonar Law]] and [[Stanley Baldwin]]. He married Alathea Gardner, the second daughter of Lord Burghclere.<ref>G.S. Fry's entry in ''Who was Who''.</ref><ref>''The Times'', Saturday, 15 October 1960; pg. 8; Issue 54903; col G: Obituary Sir Geoffrey Fry.</ref><ref>''The Times'', Friday, 28 May 1915; pg. 11; Issue 40866; col C: Forthcoming marriages.</ref>\n*[[Jennifer Ross|(Ann) Jennifer Evelyn Elizabeth Fry]] (1916\u20132003), only child of Geoffrey and Alathea Fry. She was the wife of [[Alan Ross]], the poet.\n\n===Theodore Fry and his family===\n[[Theodore Fry]] (1836\u20131912), was the son of Francis Fry (1803\u20131886). He was Liberal MP for [[Darlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Darlington]] and made baronet.  His wife, [[Sophia Fry]] n\u00e9e Pease (1837\u20131897) was a prominent philanthropist and political activist.<ref>''Times obituary'' of Theodore Fry is at [http://www.dmm.org.uk/archives/a_obit15.htm Durham Mining Museum website].</ref> Their son, John Pease Fry (1864\u20131957),<ref>J.P. Fry entry in ''Who was Who''.</ref> the second baronet, became Chairman and managing director of Bearpark Coal & Coke of [[Durham, England|Durham]].\n\n==Joseph Fry and his family==\n\nJoseph Fry (1795\u20131879),<ref>Note: he was not the Joseph Fry (1777\u20131861), who was husband of [[Elizabeth Fry]]</ref> son of the first Joseph Storrs Fry (1769\u20131835), and Mary Anne Swaine (1797\u20131886)<ref name=\"Milliagn\">''[[Milligan's Biographical dictionary of British Quakers in commerce and industry|The Biographical dictionary of British Quakers in commerce and industry]], 1775-1920'', by Edward H. Milligan, Sessions of York (2007) {{ISBN|978-1-85072-367-7}}. p191: article on Joseph Fry (1795-1879).</ref> were the parents of:\n*[[Joseph Storrs Fry II]] (1826\u20131913). Headed the chocolate firm after 1886 and was active in the Society of Friends. He never married but was known for his philanthropy.\n*Sir [[Edward Fry]] (1827\u20131918), a judge on the British Court of Appeal. Edward Fry was the father of the art critic and artist [[Roger Fry]] and the social reformers, [[Joan Mary Fry]] (1862\u20131955), [[Margery Fry]] (1874\u20131958) and [[Ruth Fry]] (1878\u20131962). His daughter, Agnes Fry (1869\u20131958) compiled his biography.\n*Albert Fry (1830?\u20131903). He worked with [[John Fowler (agricultural engineer)|John Fowler]] (1826\u20131864)<ref>See [[ODNB]] article by Jonathan Brown, \u2018Fowler, John (1826\u20131864)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, Sept 2004; online edn, May 2007 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/10010], accessed 15 Sept 2007.</ref> to develop and manufacture a drainage plough in the mid-19th century. He founded the [[Bristol Wagon & Carriage Works]].<ref>{{cite journal|last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date= 24 April 1903 |title=Obituary of Albert Fry |journal=\"The Times\" |volume= |issue=37063 |page=10 |url=}}</ref> He was a chairman of the council of the [[University of Bristol]] and, along with other members of his family and of the Wills family, a major donor<ref>''The Library of the University of Bristol, 1876-1975'' by Nicholas Lee at [http://www.bris.ac.uk/is/about/what/libraries/libraryhistory-lee.doc http://www.bris.ac.uk/is/about/what/libraries/libraryhistory-lee.doc] accessed 15 Sept 2007.</ref>\n*Susan Ann Fry (1829\u20131917) married in 1856, as his third wife, Thomas Pease and was the mother of [[Edward Reynolds Pease]] who help found the [[Fabian Society]]<ref name=\"Milligan\">''The Biographical dictionary of British Quakers in commerce and industry, 1775-1920'', by Edward H Milligan, Sessions of York (2007) {{ISBN|978-1-85072-367-7}}. pp.190B-191A.</ref> and Marian Fry Pease (1859\u20131954) who was the first female student and later a teacher at [[University College, Bristol]].<ref>John B. Thomas, \u2018Pease, Marian Fry (1859\u20131954)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/48581, accessed 26 May 2014]</ref>\n*[[Lewis Fry]] (1832\u20131921) was the Liberal, later Liberal Unionist, MP for Bristol from 1878 until 1886 and from 1895 until 1900. He was chairman of Parliamentary Committee on Town Holdings, 1886\u20131892.<ref>Lewis Fry entry in ''Who was Who''</ref>  He was a member of the [[Privy Council]]. He was the first chairman of the Council of the University of Bristol.\n*Henrietta Jane Fry (1840\u20131911) who married an ironfounder named William Whitwell in 1862.<ref name=\"Milligan\"/>\nand three other daughters, one of whom died in infancy.<ref name=\"Milligan\"/>\n\n==Other members of the family==\n\n*[[Cecil Roderick Fry]] (1890\u20131952)<ref>C.R. Fry entry in ''Who was Who''.</ref> was the last member of the family to head the chocolate firm before it merged with [[Cadburys]].\n**[[Jeremy Fry]] (1924\u20132005) was an engineer and inventor, son of Cecil Fry. Founded [[Rotork]].\n** David Fry (1918\u20131967), engineer, son of Cecil Fry.  Founded Frenchay Products.\n*[[Edwin Waterhouse]], co-founder of the accountancy practice of [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]].  His great-grandmother, Anne Fry (1755-1821), was the niece of the brothers [[Joseph Fry (type-founder)|Joseph Fry]] and William Storrs Fry.  Anne's father was another brother, John Fry (1733-1803).<ref>See common ancestor John Fry (1701 - 1775)[https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Fry-1728] click on \"Descendants\".</ref>{{Better source|reason=I doubt wiki tree is a good source. The line seems to be John Fry had a daughter, Ann, who married Jasper Capper and they had a daughter, Rebecca, who married Paul Bevan, and they had a daughter, Mary, who married Alfred Waterhouse and they are parents of Edwin (as well as two others with wiki articles).  However that is all original research (though one perhaps a bit more trustworthy than wikitree) from http://www.pennyghael.org.uk/Fry.pdf|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Other Frys==\n'''Other Quaker Frys who might or might not be related to this family are:'''\n\n*Catherine Fry, mother of [[Lewis Fry Richardson]], mathematician\n*[[Christopher Fry]], born Christopher Fry Harris (1907\u20132005), playwright\n\n''For other people with the surname \"Fry\" but probably ''not'' related to the Quaker Chocolate manufacturing Fry family see [[Fry (surname)]].''\n\n==Sources==\n*{{ODNBweb|id=10212|title=Fry, Joseph|last = Mosley|first=James Mosley}}; and the articles there on  Francis Fry (1803\u20131886), Edmund Fry (1754\u20131835), Joseph Storrs Fry (1826\u20131913), Edward Fry (1827\u20131918), and Sophia Fry n\u00e9e Pease.\n*[http://www.bath.ac.uk/~ensegb/wag.htm Bristol Wagon & Carriage Works] (references to Albert Fry)\n*[http://www.bris.ac.uk/university/history/ University of Bristol History] (references to the Fry family support in founding the university)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060211070915/http://www.frenchay.org/frys.html Frenchay Village Museum] \u2013 [[Frenchay]], [[South Gloucestershire]] is where many of the Frys lived\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Fry|short=x}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fry Family}}\n[[Category:Fry family| ]]\n[[Category:English families]]\n[[Category:People from Bristol]]\n[[Category:Quaker families]]\n", "name_user": "Crescent Rosie", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fry_family_(chocolate)"}
